{
  "text": "Let P n (e) denote the probability that the concentration of redox couples at time n differs from the predicted concentration by more than e. As n increases, it can be shown that P n (e) will tend to zero [CITATION_1] . The fluctuation decay rate, denoted Q*, is the asymptotic rate at which the number P n (e) tends to zero. The quantity P n (e) can be interpreted as the probability that the sample mean of a metabolic observable defined at instant n, differs from the asymptotic mean by more than e. We write",
